column87:
The question, "How angry do you feel about this request?" - if you wanted me to indicate only how angry I am at my hypothetical sister *specifically*, you should say that. I would not be angry at my sister, but I would be extremely angry at the *system* for letting children die of preventable health conditions unless they have enough money or can get other people to give it to them!

Also, sliders are a *terrible* way to ask us for an exact amount of money in the potentially hundreds of thousands. I would not say I would be comfortable giving exactly $1907, it's just that the scale jumped hundreds of dollars at a time, so it was impossible to input an exact amount. Just let us type it in!

column87:
I do hope that by number of siblings you meant LIVING siblings. I'm technically third, but I had a sister who got equine encephalitis* and died two years before I was born. So I only have one living sibling who's 9 years my senior.

*They didn't know this virus could infect and kill humans in the early 1970s. Evidently my sister was something like the 9th case known at the time, and my mother said that my sister was studied by pretty much everyone. It's spread by mosquitoes, and basically my folks won a lottery no one wants to win. We now know that it infects humans, but it's incredibly rare to get sick from it, and when people do, it's the very young, old, and immunocompromised. My sister was two and a half when she died from this, and that's the main kill group for this thing. :/

So now you know.

column87: I do not believe in lending money. Either I gift it or not. I would be happy to help my sister look for alternatives like organizations that help with costs, taking out a second mortgage on her home, and having a go fund me page. But I would not sacrifice my child's education to just give a family member money that they should have saved for. If they have bad health insurance then they need to put away money in an emergency fund. And if that means living in a small apartment with one television and old cars, then that is what you have to do. My husband and I below our means in order to save for the future.  If by chance I did have the $50,000 lying around and burning a hole in my pocket, and my sister had tried every other alternative, and she would be willing to go on a written budget and financial plan that I would work out with her, then I would give her the money.
